me people are short and some people aren’t the head of the class – the sooner we get on board with accepting that the better. &#10;According to you, he seems more than ready academically. And of course your son has a short attention span – he’s not yet 5!! I don’t believe any parent who says their child has a long attention span at age 4. Loud and impulsive – once again, of course for that age. Kindergarten will help direct these attributes in a more positive, acceptable direction. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="790" language="en" documentId="5385" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Bev" date="March 7, 2013 at 9:44 am" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://blogs.babycenter.com/mom_stories/03072013-the-big-kindergarten-question-to-redshirt-or-not/" topic="redshirting" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="5385" notes="" title="The big kindergarten question: To redshirt or not?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="433"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="434" end="790"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43"/></xmi:XMI>